Introduction

For this project, I analyzed loan data obtained from Prosper which was obtained from the 2009 housing crisis. I chose this data set because after seeing The Big Short last winter, I became inspired to find out about the different types of loans.

Univariate Analysis

What is the structure of your dataset?

There are 81 columns and 113,937 rows in the dataset.

What is/are the main feature(s) of your dataset?

The main features of the dataset are the Prosper score, the Prosper ratings, the borrowers employment status, the number of trades that are delinquent, and the amount by which borrowers were delinquent. The Prosper score is a risk score assigned based on historical data whose possible values fall between 1 and 10, inclusively. 1 is the lowest score (highest-risk) and 10 is the highest score (lowest-risk), and the amount delinquent is the dollar amount by which borrowers were owing at the time their profiles were pulled.

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?

Other features that would help my investigation are the EstimatedLoss, the EstimatedReturn, the CreditGrade, and possibly the homeowning status of the borrowers. The homeowning status of the borrowers would definitely impact what kinds of loans they took out, since different lifestyles have different requirements. The grade of the loans could be important because it could determine the delinquency rate since the different types of loans have different eligibility requirements. The Estimated Loss/EstimatedReturn could also give insight into the nature of the loans.

Did you create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset?

I did not create any new variables from the variables in the data set as it would have been unnecessary.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?

When I read in the CSV, I used the parameter na.string = NA to address empty values because otherwise, the code wouldnt have known how to handle empty values. I noticed that all of the values in the third histogram were either 12 months, 36 months, or 60 months. I also noticed that the borrowers interest rates and the numerical Prosper ratings followed an approximately normal distribution. A notable exception was the loans that had a Prosper rating of 7, as this number was far less frequent than the others. This was not surprising as the loans with the highest rating have the lowest risk, so the fewest people would qualify for those loans.

This plot matrix plots the total number of trades, the number of non-delinquent trades, and the number of trades opened over the last 6 months. I thought that the date of the trade would affect the number of non-delinquent trades, but there is not a very strong correlation.

On the other hand, there is a strong correlation between the total number of trades and the percentage of non-delinquent trades. This is not surprising because the number of trades would affect the borrowers ability to make good on them.

However, this does not exempt the borrower from paying off the remaining balance. The net principal loss is the amount remaining after collecting a balance.

Bivariate Analysis

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?

The last plot in the Bivariate Plots section plots the homeowning status against the alphabetical Prosper rating. It showed something very interesting: there are 56,459 non-homeowners and 57,478 homeowners, and they all took almost the same number of loans of each grade. I found this interesting because I thought that the majority of homeowners would have taken loans that were rated A or AA because they would likely have had more disposable income, but this was clearly not the case.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?

I expected a nearly perfect negative correlation between the number of delinquent trades and the dollar amount by which borrowers were delinquent. I thought that the people who had fewer delinquent trades would have paid off most of their debts, and therefore had less money delinquent but this was not the case: the trendline shows an odd spike, and the relationship mostly fluctuates, thereby indicating a moderately strong negative relationship, at best.

I also expected a perfect correlation between the borrowed principal amount and the outstanding principal amount because I worked under the assumption that the more money someone borrowed, the more they would owe later on, but the relationship is almost the reverse of the relationship between the number of trades delinquent and the delinquency amount-there is only a moderate correlation at best.

What was the strongest relationship you found?

The correlation between gross principal loss and net principal loss is very strong, if not nearly perfect. This is not surprising since the net principal loss is equal to the difference between gross charge-offs and recoveries of debt, so the net principal loss is calculated from the gross principal loss. However, there some very curious outpus: according to the output from the summary function calls, the lowest value for this quantity in the dataset is -94.2. Its lowest value is -954.60. The negative amounts could be due to overpayment, which would require the creditor to refund some money.

Multivariate Analysis

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?

I was not surprised that so many full-time workers took loans with higher ProsperScores. They have the income to support it, so they are more likely to be approved to take safer loans because of their improved financial standing. In this section, I also explored the relationship between the borrowers homeowning status and the ProsperScores of their loans. I was surprised to see that the split was almost perfectly equal. This could be because of differences in housing units (that is, some apartments are better than others, etc. These kinds of differences would account for the differences in the amounts and types of loans.)

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?

It was interesting that retired people had such a small proportion of non-delinquent trades. I thought that retired people would be closer to the top because they would have most likely had the most money saved up and therefore have fewer non-delinquencies, and because they would likely have had less reason to borrow money in the first place. This result could be due to the fact that retirees have fewer requirements as far as finances are concerned since their mortgage payments are most likely over and their children will have moved out.

Final Plots and Summary

Plot One

Description One

This is a plot of customer payments versus gross principal loss. The customer payment is the total payment made by the borrower before charge-off and the gross principal loss is the amount that has been charged off. I expected a negative correlation, but the trend starts off somewhat inconsistent before decreasing at an increasing rate.

Plot Two

Description Two

The above boxplot grid shows the borrowers employment status and the percentage of their trades that are delinquent. The people whose status is Employed" had the lowest percentages of non-delinquent trades. This is odd as I expected this from retired people. It is unclear what the definition of Employed is since the data set differentiates among full-time, part-time, and self-employed.

Plot Three

Description Three

This boxplot grid shows the borrowers employment status and the numerical Prosper ratings of their loans. The distribution of Prosper ratings among Employed people is strange: there is an even split among those who took loans rated above and below 4. Unsurprisingly, Not Employed people took loans that were rated very low. It stands to reason that the majority of full-time workers took loans rated above 4 because they are most likely to have the income and stability to qualify for those loans.

Reflection

There were a lot of interesting relationships between the data points in this set. I was surprised at how evenly the Prosper ratings were distributed among homeowners and non-homeowners alike because I assumed that the former group would have had a far higher concentration of loans rated A or AA. I was also surprised that the estimated loss and estimated return did not have a perfect negative correlation. I assumed this because estimated return is calculated from estimated loss, but the trend starts off somewhat inconsistent before decreasing steadily.

A big problem with the data set was the separation among employment statuses. It is never established what Other entails, and it is somewhat unncessary to differentiate among Employed and Full-time, Part-time, and Self-Employed. This difference shifted the results and therefore it is difficult to draw any meaningful conclusions since Employed is never properly defined.

For future analyses, it could be worth investigating why the data set distinguishes among Full-time, Part-time, Employed, and Self-Employed since these should all fall under the umbrella of Employed. Another important question for the future would be, What is the significance of the Other category? It is never explained what this category is for.
